Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, (for all v1, (for all v2, (if v2 is a natural number and v1 is a natural number and v0 is a natural number then (if v2 \NATleq v1 and v1 \NATleq v0 then v2 \NATleq v0))))
Proof:
  n \NATleq m and m \NATleq k
  if n is equal to m and m is equal to k then the thesis holds
  if n is equal to m and m \NATless k then the thesis holds
  if n \NATless m and m is equal to k then the thesis holds
  if n \NATless m and m \NATless k then the thesis holds
Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, (for all v1, (for all v2, (if v2 is a natural number and v1 is a natural number and v0 is a natural number then (if v2 \NATleq v1 and v1 \NATless v0 then v2 \NATless v0))))
Proof:
  n \NATleq m and m \NATless k
  if n is equal to m then n \NATless k
  if n \NATless m then n \NATless k
Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, (for all v1, (for all v2, (if v2 is a natural number and v1 is a natural number and v0 is a natural number then (if v2 \NATless v1 and v1 \NATleq v0 then v2 \NATless v0))))
Proof:
  n \NATless m and m \NATleq k
  if m is equal to k then n \NATless k
  if m \NATless k then n \NATless k
Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, (for all v1, (if v1 is a natural number and v0 is a natural number then (if v1 \NATless v0 then v1 \NATplus \NATone \NATleq v0)))
Proof:
  n \NATless m
  k is a natural number and k is positive and m is equal to n \NATplus k
  if k is equal to \NATone then the thesis holds
  Proof:
    m is equal to n \NATplus \NATone
    n \NATplus \NATone \NATleq m
  Qed.
  if it is wrong that k is equal to \NATone then the thesis holds
  Proof:
    l is a natural number and k is equal to l \NATplus \NATone
    m is equal to n \NATplus l \NATplus \NATone and n \NATplus l \NATplus \NATone is equal to n \NATplus l \NATplus \NATone and n \NATplus l \NATplus \NATone is equal to n \NATplus \NATone \NATplus l
    l is positive
    n \NATplus \NATone \NATless m
  Qed.
Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, (for all v1, (if v1 is a natural number and v0 is a natural number then (v1 \NATless v0 or v1 is equal to v0 or v0 \NATless v1)))
Proof:
  \Phi is a class and (if \Nat is a set then \Phi is a set) and for all v0, (v0 is an element of \Phi iff (v0 is an element of \Nat and v0 is an object and (n \NATless v0 or n is equal to v0 or v0 \NATless n)))
  \NATzero is an element of \Phi
  for all v0, (if v0 is an element of \Phi then v0 \NATplus \NATone is an element of \Phi)
  Proof:
    m' is an element of \Phi
    if n \NATless m' then the thesis holds
    if n is equal to m' then the thesis holds
    if m' \NATless n then the thesis holds
    Proof:
      k is a natural number and k is positive and n is equal to m' \NATplus k
      if k is equal to \NATone then the thesis holds
      if it is wrong that k is equal to \NATone then the thesis holds
      Proof:
        l is a natural number and n is equal to m' \NATplus \NATone \NATplus l
        m' \NATplus \NATone \NATless n
        Proof:
          l is positive
        Qed.
      Qed.
    Qed.
  Qed.
  for all v0, (if v0 is a natural number then v0 is an element of \Phi)
  n \NATless m or n is equal to m or m \NATless n
Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, (for all v1, (if v1 is a natural number and v0 is a natural number then (it is wrong that v1 \NATless v0 iff v0 \NATleq v1)))
Proof:
  if it is wrong that n \NATless m then the thesis holds
  Proof:
    n is equal to m or m \NATless n
    m \NATleq n
  Qed.
  if m \NATleq n then the thesis holds
  Proof:
    n \NATless m
    n \NATleq m
    n is equal to m
    falsity holds
  Qed.
Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, (for all v1, (if v1 is a natural number and v0 is a natural number then (if v1 \NATless v0 and v0 \NATleq v1 \NATplus \NATone then v0 is equal to v1 \NATplus \NATone)))
Proof:
  n \NATless m and m \NATleq n \NATplus \NATone
  k is a natural number and k is positive and m is equal to n \NATplus k
  l is a natural number and n \NATplus \NATone is equal to m \NATplus l
  n \NATplus \NATone is equal to m \NATplus l and m \NATplus l is equal to n \NATplus k \NATplus l and n \NATplus k \NATplus l is equal to n \NATplus k \NATplus l
  k \NATplus l is equal to \NATone
  l is equal to \NATzero
  Proof:
    it is wrong that the thesis holds
    \NATzero \NATless k and \NATzero \NATless l
    if k is equal to \NATone and l is equal to \NATone then the thesis holds
    Proof:
      k \NATplus l is equal to \NATtwo and it is wrong that \NATtwo is equal to \NATone
      falsity holds
    Qed.
    if k is equal to \NATone and it is wrong that l is equal to \NATone then the thesis holds
    Proof:
      \NATone \NATless l
      \NATone \NATplus l \NATless k \NATplus l and \NATone \NATless \NATone \NATplus l
      falsity holds
    Qed.
    if it is wrong that k is equal to \NATone and l is equal to \NATone then the thesis holds
    Proof:
      \NATone \NATless k
      k \NATplus \NATone \NATless k \NATplus l and \NATone \NATless k \NATplus \NATone
      falsity holds
    Qed.
    if it is wrong that k is equal to \NATone and it is wrong that l is equal to \NATone then the thesis holds
    Proof:
      a is a natural number and b is a natural number and (k is equal to a \NATplus \NATone and l is equal to b \NATplus \NATone)
      Proof:
        it is wrong that k is equal to \NATzero and it is wrong that l is equal to \NATzero
      Qed.
      k is equal to a \NATplus \NATone and l is equal to b \NATplus \NATone
      \NATone \NATless k and \NATone \NATless l
      Proof:
        a is positive and b is positive
      Qed.
    Qed.
  Qed.
  n \NATplus \NATone is equal to m \NATplus l and m \NATplus l is equal to m \NATplus \NATzero and m \NATplus \NATzero is equal to m
Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, (for all v1, (if v1 is a natural number and v0 is a natural number then (if v1 \NATleq v0 and v0 \NATless v1 \NATplus \NATone then v1 is equal to v0)))
Proof:
  n \NATleq m and m \NATless n \NATplus \NATone
  if n is equal to m then the thesis holds
  if n \NATless m then the thesis holds
  Proof:
    n \NATless m and m \NATleq n \NATplus \NATone
    n is equal to m
  Qed.
Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, (if v0 is a natural number then it is wrong that for some v1, (v1 is a natural number and v0 \NATless v1 and v1 \NATless v0 \NATplus \NATone))
Proof:
  it is wrong that the thesis holds
  m is a natural number and n \NATless m and m \NATless n \NATplus \NATone
  n \NATless m and m \NATleq n \NATplus \NATone and (n \NATleq m and m \NATless n \NATplus \NATone)
  m is equal to n \NATplus \NATone and m is equal to n
  n is equal to n \NATplus \NATone
  falsity holds
Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, (if v0 is a natural number then \NATone \NATleq v0 \NATplus \NATone)
Proof:
  if n is equal to \NATzero then the thesis holds
  if it is wrong that n is equal to \NATzero then the thesis holds
  Proof:
    \NATzero \NATless n
    \NATzero \NATplus \NATone \NATless n \NATplus \NATone and \NATzero \NATplus \NATone is equal to \NATone
  Qed.
Qed.

Theorem (preservation_of_ordering_under_right_addition):
  for all v0, (for all v1, (for all v2, (if v2 is a natural number and v1 is a natural number and v0 is a natural number then (v2 \NATless v1 iff v2 \NATplus v0 \NATless v1 \NATplus v0))))
Proof:
  if n \NATless m then the thesis holds
  Proof:
    l is a natural number and l is positive and m is equal to n \NATplus l
    m \NATplus k is equal to n \NATplus l \NATplus k and n \NATplus l \NATplus k is equal to n \NATplus k \NATplus l
    n \NATplus k \NATless m \NATplus k
  Qed.
  if n \NATplus k \NATless m \NATplus k then the thesis holds
  Proof:
    l is a natural number and l is positive and m \NATplus k is equal to n \NATplus k \NATplus l
    n \NATplus k \NATplus l is equal to n \NATplus k \NATplus l and n \NATplus k \NATplus l is equal to n \NATplus l \NATplus k and n \NATplus l \NATplus k is equal to n \NATplus l \NATplus k
    m \NATplus k is equal to n \NATplus l \NATplus k
    m is equal to n \NATplus l
    n \NATless m
  Qed.
Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, (for all v1, (for all v2, (if v2 is a natural number and v1 is a natural number and v0 is a natural number then (v2 \NATless v1 iff v0 \NATplus v2 \NATless v0 \NATplus v1))))
Proof:
  k \NATplus n is equal to n \NATplus k and k \NATplus m is equal to m \NATplus k
  k \NATplus n \NATless k \NATplus m iff n \NATplus k \NATless m \NATplus k
Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, (for all v1, (for all v2, (if v2 is a natural number and v1 is a natural number and v0 is a natural number then (v2 \NATleq v1 iff v0 \NATplus v2 \NATleq v0 \NATplus v1))))
Proof:
Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, (for all v1, (for all v2, (if v2 is a natural number and v1 is a natural number and v0 is a natural number then (v2 \NATleq v1 iff v2 \NATplus v0 \NATleq v1 \NATplus v0))))
Proof:
Qed.

Theorem (wellfoundedness_of_ordering):
  for all v0, (if v0 is a subclass of \Nat and it is wrong that v0 is empty then for some v1, (v1 is an element of v0 and for all v2, (if v2 is an element of v0 then v1 \NATleq v2)))
Proof:
  it is wrong that the thesis holds
  for all v0, (if v0 is an element of A then for some v1, (v1 is an element of A and v1 \NATless v0))
  Proof:
    n is an element of A
    it is wrong that for some v0, (v0 is an element of A and v0 \NATless n)
    for all v0, (if v0 is an element of A then n \NATleq v0)
    falsity holds
  Qed.
  \Phi is a class and (if \Nat is a set then \Phi is a set) and for all v0, (v0 is an element of \Phi iff (v0 is an element of \Nat and v0 is an object and for all v1, (if v1 is an element of A then v0 \NATless v1)))
  \NATzero is an element of \Phi
  Proof:
    it is wrong that \NATzero is an element of A
    for all v0, (if v0 is an element of A then \NATzero \NATless v0)
    \NATzero is an element of \Phi
  Qed.
  for all v0, (if v0 is an element of \Phi then v0 \NATplus \NATone is an element of \Phi)
  Proof:
    n is an element of \Phi
    for all v0, (if v0 is an element of A then n \NATless v0)
    it is wrong that n \NATplus \NATone is an element of \Phi
    m is an element of A and it is wrong that n \NATplus \NATone \NATless m
    n \NATless m and m \NATleq n \NATplus \NATone
    m is equal to n \NATplus \NATone
    falsity holds
  Qed.
  for all v0, (if v0 is a natural number then v0 is an element of \Phi)
  for all v0, (if v0 is a natural number then for all v1, (if v1 is an element of A then v0 \NATless v1))
  it is wrong that for some v0, (v0 is an element of A)
  falsity holds
Qed.

Theorem (induction_II):
  for all v0, (if v0 is a class then (if for all v1, (if v1 is an element of \Nat then (if for all v2, (if v2 is a predecessor of v1 then v2 is an element of v0) then v1 is an element of v0)) then for all v1, (if v1 is a natural number then v1 is an element of v0)))
Proof:
  it is wrong that the thesis holds
  n is a natural number and it is wrong that n is an element of A
  n is an element of \Nat \SETdiff A
  m is an element of \Nat \SETdiff A and for all v0, (if v0 is an element of \Nat \SETdiff A then m \NATleq v0)
  for all v0, (if v0 is a predecessor of m then it is wrong that v0 is an element of \Nat \SETdiff A)
  for all v0, (if v0 is a predecessor of m then v0 is an element of A)
  m is an element of A
  falsity holds
Qed.

Theorem (induction_III):
  for all v0, (if v0 is a class then for all v1, (if v1 is a natural number and v1 is an element of v0 then (if for all v2, (if v2 is an element of \Natgeqthan{ v1 } then (if v2 is an element of v0 then v2 \NATplus \NATone is an element of v0)) then for all v2, (if v2 is an element of \Natgeqthan{ v1 } then v2 is an element of v0))))
Proof:
  \Phi is a class and (if \Nat is a set then \Phi is a set) and for all v0, (v0 is an element of \Phi iff (v0 is an element of \Nat and v0 is an object and (if k \NATleq v0 then v0 is an element of A)))
  \NATzero is an element of \Phi
  Proof:
    if k \NATleq \NATzero then (\NATzero is equal to k and k is an element of A)
  Qed.
  for all v0, (if v0 is an element of \Phi then v0 \NATplus \NATone is an element of \Phi)
  Proof:
    n is an element of \Phi
    if k \NATleq n \NATplus \NATone then n \NATplus \NATone is an element of A
    Proof:
      k \NATleq n \NATplus \NATone
      if n \NATless k then the thesis holds
      Proof:
        n \NATplus \NATone is equal to k
        n \NATplus \NATone is an element of A
      Qed.
      if k \NATleq n then the thesis holds
      Proof:
        n is an element of A
        n \NATplus \NATone is an element of A
      Qed.
    Qed.
    n \NATplus \NATone is an element of \Phi
  Qed.
  for all v0, (if v0 is a natural number then v0 is an element of \Phi)
  for all v0, (if v0 is an element of \Natgeqthan{ k } then v0 is an element of A)
Qed.

Definition:
  for all v0, (for all v1, (if v1 is a natural number and v0 is a natural number then for all v2, ((v2 is equal to \NATsegment{ v1 }{ v0 }) iff (v2 is a class and (if \Nat is a set then v2 is a set) and for all v3, (v3 is an element of v2 iff (v3 is an element of \Nat and v3 is an object and (v1 \NATleq v3 and v3 \NATleq v0)))))))

Theorem:
  for all v0, (for all v1, (if v1 is a natural number and v0 is a natural number then (if \NATsegment{ \NATone }{ v1 } is equal to \NATsegment{ \NATone }{ v0 } then v1 is equal to v0)))
Proof:
  \NATsegment{ \NATone }{ n } is equal to \NATsegment{ \NATone }{ m }
  if n is equal to \NATzero then the thesis holds
  Proof:
    \NATsegment{ \NATone }{ n } is equal to \SETempty
    \NATsegment{ \NATone }{ m } is equal to \SETempty
    it is wrong that for some v0, (v0 is an element of \Nat and \NATone \NATleq v0 and v0 \NATleq m)
    m is equal to \NATzero
    n is equal to m
  Qed.
  if m is equal to \NATzero then the thesis holds
  Proof:
    \NATsegment{ \NATone }{ m } is equal to \SETempty
    \NATsegment{ \NATone }{ n } is equal to \SETempty
    it is wrong that for some v0, (v0 is an element of \Nat and \NATone \NATleq v0 and v0 \NATleq n)
    n is equal to \NATzero
    n is equal to m
  Qed.
  if \NATone \NATleq n and \NATone \NATleq m then the thesis holds
  Proof:
    for all v0, (if v0 is an element of \Nat then ((\NATone \NATleq v0 and v0 \NATleq n) iff (\NATone \NATleq v0 and v0 \NATleq m)))
    for all v0, (if v0 is an element of \Nat then (v0 \NATleq n iff v0 \NATleq m))
    n is equal to m
    Proof:
      it is wrong that n is equal to m
      m \NATless n or n \NATless m
      if m \NATless n then the thesis holds
      Proof:
        k is equal to m \NATplus \NATone
        k \NATleq n and it is wrong that k \NATleq m
        it is wrong that (k \NATleq n iff k \NATleq m)
        falsity holds
      Qed.
      if n \NATless m then the thesis holds
      Proof:
        k is equal to n \NATplus \NATone
        k \NATleq m and it is wrong that k \NATleq m
        it is wrong that (k \NATleq n iff k \NATleq m)
        falsity holds
      Qed.
    Qed.
  Qed.
Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, (if v0 is a natural number then \NATsegment{ \NATone }{ v0 \NATplus \NATone } is equal to \NATsegment{ \NATone }{ v0 } \SETunion \SETsingleton{ v0 \NATplus \NATone })
Proof:
  \NATsegment{ \NATone }{ n \NATplus \NATone } is a subclass of \NATsegment{ \NATone }{ n } \SETunion \SETsingleton{ n \NATplus \NATone } and \NATsegment{ \NATone }{ n } \SETunion \SETsingleton{ n \NATplus \NATone } is a subclass of \NATsegment{ \NATone }{ n \NATplus \NATone }
Qed.

